The problem requires finding a lower bound for \(P(|Y / n - 0.25| < 0.05)\) when \(Y\) follows a binomial distribution \(b(n, 0.25)\) and \(n = 500\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality for the sample proportion \(\hat{p} = Y / n\), which has mean \(\mu = p = 0.25\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = p(1 - p) / n\):

- \(\sigma^2 = (0.25)(0.75) / 500 = 0.000375\)
- \(\sigma = \sqrt{0.000375} \approx 0.019365\)

The event is \(|\hat{p} - p| < 0.05\). Set \(k\sigma = 0.05\), so \(k = 0.05 / \sigma \approx 0.05 / 0.019365 \approx 2.581\). Then, \(k^2 \approx 6.662\).

By Chebyshev's inequality, \(P(|\hat{p} - p| \geq k\sigma) \leq 1/k^2\), so:
- \(P(|\hat{p} - p| < k\sigma) \geq 1 - 1/k^2 \approx 1 - 1/6.662 \approx 1 - 0.1501 = 0.8499\)

Using exact fractions:
- \(p(1 - p) = (1/4)(3/4) = 3/16\)
- \(\sigma^2 = (3/16) / 500 = 3/(16 \times 500) = 3/8000\)
- \(k = 0.05 / \sqrt{3/8000} = (1/20) \times \sqrt{8000/3} = (1/20) \times \sqrt{8000}/\sqrt{3} = (1/20) \times 40\sqrt{5}/\sqrt{3} = 2\sqrt{5}/\sqrt{3} = 2\sqrt{15}/3\)
- \(k^2 = (2\sqrt{15}/3)^2 = 4 \times 15 / 9 = 60/9 = 20/3\)
- \(1/k^2 = 3/20 = 0.15\)
- \(P(|\hat{p} - p| < 0.05) \geq 1 - 3/20 = 17/20 = 0.85\)

The lower bound is exactly 0.85. This is a valid lower bound as Chebyshev's inequality applies to any distribution with finite variance, and the binomial distribution meets this criterion.

