Using the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The probability \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3})\) is standardized to the normal variable \(Z\):

- Lower bound: \(Z = \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} = 0\)
- Upper bound: \(Z = \frac{\frac{2}{3} - 0.5}{1/12} = \frac{\frac{1}{6}}{1/12} = 2\)

Thus, \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3}) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is standard normal. Using the standard normal distribution, \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\) and \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.9772\), so:

