Solution: The ionization energy of \(\mathrm{H}_2\) is calculated using the dissociation energies and the ionization energy of the hydrogen atom. The dissociation energy \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2) = 4.478 \, \mathrm{eV}\) corresponds to \(\mathrm{H}_2 \rightarrow 2\mathrm{H}\), and \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^{+}) = 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}\) corresponds to \(\mathrm{H}_2^{+} \rightarrow \mathrm{H} + \mathrm{H}^{+}\). The ionization energy of the hydrogen atom \(\mathrm{IE}(\mathrm{H}) = 13.598 \, \mathrm{eV}\) is required for the calculation.

