Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons with a wavelength of 300 nm is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{hcN_A}{\lambda}\), where \(h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J·s}\), \(c = 3.00 \times 10^8  \text{m/s}\), \(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}  \text{mol}^{-1}\), and \(\lambda = 300 \times 10^{-9}  \text{m}\).

