\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{300 \times 10^{-9}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19}  \text{J}.
\]

Then, multiply by Avogadro's number for one mole:  
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5  \text{J/mol} = 399.0  \text{kJ/mol}.
\]

Rounding to three significant figures (consistent with the wavelength of 300 nm), the energy is 399 kJ/mol.

This photon energy (399 kJ/mol) is very close to the typical single-bond energy of 400 kJ/mol, indicating that UV photons of this wavelength have sufficient energy to break such bonds.

